data.value:
Here at Heathrow, we make sure that our customers enjoy their time with us.
If you need any help, you can or read the FAQs to solve your problem.
-What is the current airport tax imposed? Airport tax is called Air Passenger Duty (APD) and is imposed on passengers by the government. Heathrow is not involved in levying or collecting this tax. It is paid when passengers book their ticket with the airline and collected by the Government once the journey has taken place. here are different rates of APD depending on the ticket types and journey type (EU/non-EU).
-If you had fewer shops, could you manage more flights? The biggest constraints on the number of flights are runway space and aircraft parking bays. The number of shops has little impact on the number of flights running.
-What is Heathrow’s position on night flights? We understand that there's a fine balance between the economic benefits of early morning flights and the disruption it can cause to local residents. The number of flights we are able to operate is strictly controlled by the Department for Transport.
-How is Heathrow regulated? We comply with strict regulations set by the Department for Transport governing many aspects of our operation. The price we charge airlines is set by the Civil Aviation Authority.
